+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Codex on OpenBSD: current_exe(3) behavior
+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

On OpenBSD, Rust's std::env::current_exe() can fail to resolve the executable
path when the command is invoked via PATH lookup.

To avoid this issue, run Codex using a full path (for example,
`/usr/local/bin/codex`) or define shell aliases/functions that invoke the full
path explicitly.

Reference:
https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/60560

+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Codex on OpenBSD: optional companion tools
+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The package is intentionally minimal. Some model-requested workflows may work
better if you install additional packages:

- shells/bash
  Why: Codex shell guidance commonly uses bash-style invocation and non-macOS
  shell fallback preference checks bash before zsh/sh.
  Source rationale: codex-rs/core/src/tools/spec.rs and codex-rs/core/src/shell.rs

- textproc/ripgrep
  Why: the grep_files tool executes `rg` directly; without ripgrep, that tool
  call returns an explicit runtime error.
  Source rationale: codex-rs/core/src/tools/handlers/grep_files.rs

- devel/git
  Why: git-aware helpers and repository metadata features degrade when git is
  not present, though Codex itself can still run.
  Source rationale: codex-rs/core/src/git_info.rs

+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Codex on OpenBSD: upstream feature flags
+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Upstream codex-rs includes many feature flags, with several disabled by default
and some platform-specific or under development (see codex-rs/core/src/features.rs).

Future OpenBSD packaging work may expose selected feature sets as variants
or split packages when they are stable and have clear dependency boundaries.
